---

## Dot Notation

<div style="background-color: #F5F7F8; color: #000000; padding: 15px; border-radius: 10px; width: 90%; margin: 20px auto;">
       <p style="font-size: 14pt; line-height: 1.2; margin-top: 10px;">
        Dot notation accesses an object's attributes or methods using a dot (.)
    </p>
    <ul>
    <li style="font-size: 14pt; font-weight: bold;">painter.move()</li><br>
    <li style="font-size: 14pt; font-weight: bold;">painter.turn_left()</li>
    </ul>
   
</div>

## Getting Started with Objects

<table border="1" width="100%" cellpadding="10">
        <tr>
            <td width="33%">
                <img src="https://images.code.org/7d0849ab4adda8a45784b7b4fd541339-image-1741277550544.png" alt="painter = Painter()" width="130%">
            </td>
            <td width="67%" style="font-size:14pt;">
            First, <b>instantiate</b> the object by creating a new instance of the <code>Painter</code> class. <br><br> This is done by assigning the <code> Painter()</code> object to a variable.<br> <i>Here, the variable name is painter, but you can use any name.</i> 
            </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td width="33%">
                <img src="https://images.code.org/069ae6b084ee5e4a0a89a6ad174df043-image-1741277578060.png" alt="painter.move()" width="100%">
            </td>
            <td width="67%" style="font-size:14pt;">
                Now that new object has been <b>instantiated</b>, it has access to the methods defined by the <code>Painter</code>class. <br><br> You can use <b>dot notation</b> to call the methods, like <code>painter.move()</code> or <code>painter.turn_left()</code>
            </td>
        </tr>
 </table>

## Let's try! 
MARKDOWN
